== Characteristic organic reactions
#point[
Interpret and use the following terminology associated with types of organic compounds and reactions:
#set enum(numbering: "(a)")
+ homologous series
+ saturated and unsaturated
+ homolytic and heterolytic fission
+ free radical, initiation, propagation, termination
+ nucleophile, electrophile, nucleophilic, electrophilic
+ addition, substitution, elimination, hydrolysis, condensation
+ oxidation and reduction
(in equations for organic redox reactions, the symbol [O] can be used to represent one atom of oxygen
from an oxidising agent and the symbol [H] to represent one atom of hydrogen from a reducing agent)
]
A _homologous series_ is a group of organic compounds having the same functional group, the same
general formula and similar chemical properties.

A _saturated_ hydrocarbon is that where all the carbon--carbon bonds are single, and an
unsaturated hydrocarbon is that where at least one carbon--carbon bond is either double or
triple.

Fission is the breakage of a covalent bond. It is of two types.
- _Homolytic fission_ is where the atoms involved each get one electron from the bond. This forms
  two radicals.
  $ #ch("X--Y->X* + Y*") $
- _Heterolytic fission_ is where one of the atoms involved gets both the bonding electrons. This
  forms an anion and a cation.
  $ #ch("X--Y -> X- + Y+") $

A _free radical_ is a species that possesses one or more unpaired electrons. In reactions called
_free radical substitution_, the reaction progresses via steps classified as _initiation_, 
_propagation_ and _termination_. This is elaborated later.

A _nucleophile_ is a species attracted to positive charges, the species itself may be (partially)
negatively charged. An _electrophile_ is the opposite. The words _nucleophilic_ and
_electrophilic_ are simply adjective forms of the previous.

_Addition_ reactions are where reactants form one product only. _Elimination_ reactions are where
the functional group is removed from the organic compound being reacted with. _Hydrolysis_ occurs
when water is absorbed into an organic compound, giving two or more organic compounds. 
_Condensation_ is when water or a small molecule is released from a compound.

The above are descriptions for types of organic reactions, elaborations on which will follow.
