== Isomerism: structural isomerism and stereoisomerism
#point[Describe structural isomerism and its division into chain, positional and functional group
isomerism]
_Structural isomerism_ arises among molecules that have the same molecular formula but different
structural formulae. It is of the following types
- *Chain.* Arises when branching occurs within the carbon chain.
- *Positional.*  Arises due to change in position of side groups.
- *Functional group.* Arises when the functional groups of the isomers are different.

#point[Describe stereoisomerism and its division into geometrical (cis/trans) and optical isomerism
(use of E/Z nomenclature is acceptable but is not required)]
_Stereoisomerism_ arises amongst molecules of same structural formula but different spatial
arrangements of of the atoms. It is of two types
- *Geometrical (cis/trans).* Geometrical isomerism arises due to the limited rotational capability
  of $pi$ bonds in #ch("C==C"). Geometrical isomers can either be _trans_ or _cis_. In _cis_
  isomers, the heavier side groups are on the same side of the carbon, and in _trans_ isomers,
  the heavier side groups are on opposite sides of the carbon.
- *Optical (enantiomerism).* Optical isomerism arises when when two molecules with same
  the structural formula that cannot be superimposed. This is a property of a _chiral carbon_
  or a _chiral centre_ which has bonded to it four different side groups.

